<div class="biography parbase section">









<div id="cqBioComponent">
<div id="bioTeaser"><div class="image "><img margin="0" src="/content/ryerson/criminology/about-us/faculty-staff/for-faculty/faculty-news-and-events/upcoming-events/police-accountability/jcr%3acontent/center/uiwcolumns/conContainer_0_0/biography/image.img.jpg/1508877089165.jpg" alt="Police Accountability Forum" title="police_accountability_web_thumb2" class="cq-dd-image"><br></div>
	<div class="text"><h2>
    “My officers acted in good faith” Ryerson Forum on Police Oversight, Accountability and Public Consent</h2></div>
        <div id="title">
        <h5>Title:</h5>
        <p>Criminology</p>
        </div>
        
        <div id="address">
        <h5>Office:</h5>
        <p>Department of Criminology</p>
        </div>
        
        </div>
        
        <div id="specialization">
        <h5>Specialization:</h5>
        <p>Department of Criminology</p>
        </div>
        
        <div id="biography">
        <h5>Biography:</h5>
        <p><div class="image_cap_block"><p><strong>Forum Venue:&nbsp;</strong>Tecumseh Auditorium (Oakham House),&nbsp;63 Gould St., Toronto, Ontario M5B 1E9</p>
<p><strong>Forum Dates: &nbsp;</strong>Tuesday, November 14, 2017, 8 a.m. - 5 p.m.</p>
<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>
<p><strong><span class="fontSizeLarge">Welcome!</span></strong></p>
<p>We are inviting you to a one-day forum on the very important and current topic of police oversight and accountability, and its impact on public consent.&nbsp; For this event we have assembled a distinguished line-up of academic experts, community activists and policy makers from a wide variety of backgrounds.</p>
<p>As you may know, the Ontario government has committed to bring forward legislation to strengthen police oversight in the province in response to the review by Justice Michael Tulloch.&nbsp; Justice Tulloch will be present at this event to provide the context and thinking underlying his recommendations.</p>
<p>This forum will focus on how oversight, professionalization and education/training can enhance public accountability.</p>
<p>This is a timely forum. &nbsp;Recent police-community interactions have underscored the important connection between effective systems of oversight and accountability, and public consent:</p>
<ul>
<li>In Toronto, the strong reaction to the refusal of the provincial Special Investigations Unit (SIU) to release information about its investigation of the Andrew Loku death led to the independent review of police oversight by Justice Michael Tulloch of the Ontario Court of Appeal.</li>
<li>In Thunder Bay, the performance of the police services board in addressing issues between the Indigenous community and the police service caused Ontario Civilian Police Commission (OCPC) to request Senator Murray Sinclair to examine the effectiveness of police governance in that community.</li>
<li>The years of protest about police handling of missing and murdered Indigenous women finally prompted the federal government to order a national inquiry.</li>
</ul>
<p>We hope you will join us at this forum. &nbsp;</p>
</div>
</p>
        </div>
        
        <div id="department">
        <h5>Department:</h5>
        <p>This forum will focus on how oversight, professionalization and education/training can enhance public accountability.</p>
        </div>
        
    

    </div>


<div class="clear"></div></div>
