<div class="accordion">
    <div class="header">Program</div>
	<div class="content">
	<div class="tab3 parsys"><div class="table uiwTable parbase section">




















 


 


   
    <!-- 
    **note changes made above in normal non preview css styles
    repeat the style writing above and append X at the end of the component id for preview
     --> 
   
    
    <div id="toolbarObj749859624" class="allToolbarSelector"></div>
    
    
    
    
<script>                                                       

</script>  

    <div id="component749859624" class="tableComponent">
        
    <div class="tableContainer"> 

	

    <table width="100%" border="1" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="5">
<tbody><tr><td width="30%" valign="top">8:00 - 8:30 a.m.</td>
<td valign="top">REGISTRATION</td>
</tr><tr><td valign="top">&nbsp;</td>
<td>BREAKFAST</td>
</tr><tr><td>8:30 - 8:45 a.m.</td>
<td><p><strong>Opening: </strong>Elder Joanne Dallaire</p>
<p><strong>Welcome:</strong> Alok Mukherjee</p>
<p><strong>Symposium Chair:</strong> Dr. Denise O’Neil Green</p>
</td>
</tr><tr><td>8:45 - 9:30 a.m.</td>
<td><p><strong><u>The Tulloch Report: Context, Considerations, Conclusions</u></strong></p>
<p>Remarks followed by Q&amp;A</p>
<p><strong>Speaker:</strong> Justice Michael Tulloch</p>
<p><strong>Moderator:</strong> Graham Hudson</p>
</td>
</tr><tr><td>9:30 a.m. - &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; 12:00 p.m.</td>
<td><p><strong><u>Problematizing Police Oversight: The Politics, Purpose and Function of Civilian Oversight</u></strong></p>
<p>The session will explore questions such as: Why independent civilian oversight of policing? What are the key drivers for the demand for independent oversight? What constitutes effective oversight from a community perspective from the perspectives of the state, the police and the public?</p>
<p><strong>Presenter:</strong> Professor Kent Roach</p>
<p><strong>Discussants:</strong> Ms Caitlyn Kasper, Mr Fred Kaustinen, Mr Anthony Morgan</p>
<p><strong>Moderator:</strong> Professor Tammy Landau</p>
</td>
</tr><tr><td>12:00 - &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; 12:45 p.m.</td>
<td>LUNCH</td>
</tr><tr><td>12:45 - &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp; 2:15 p.m.</td>
<td><p><strong><u>Professionalization of Policing and Public Accountability</u></strong></p>
<p>The session will examine the concept of professionalization through a College of Policing, currently being established in England and recommended in the Tulloch Report. Drawing on experiences from other jurisdictions and professions, like teaching, nursing and engineering, the session will address questions such as:&nbsp;</p>
<p>Does professionalization contribute to public accountability? Does it have any impact on professional culture, and, if so, how it may influence or change police culture?</p>
<p><strong>Presenter:</strong> Professor Chris MacDonald</p>
<p><strong>Discussants:</strong> Ms Sandra Nishikawa, Dr Michael Salvatori, Mr Matt Torigian</p>
<p><strong>Moderator:</strong> Professor Nancy Walton</p>
</td>
</tr><tr><td>2:15 - 2:30 p.m.</td>
<td>BREAK</td>
</tr><tr><td>2:30 - 4:00 p.m.</td>
<td><p><strong><u>Police Training and Education, and Public Accountability</u></strong></p>
<p>The session will consider (1) whether there is any relationship between enhanced police education and training recommended in the Tulloch Report and public accountability, and, if so, (2) what would be the education universities could provide to achieve this objective.</p>
<p><strong>Presenter:</strong> Dr Aidan Lockhart</p>
<p><strong>Discussants:</strong> Mr Gerry McNeilly, Ms Noa Mendelsohn, Professor Pam Palmater</p>
<p><strong>Moderator:</strong> Professor Anne-Marie Singh</p>
</td>
</tr><tr><td>4:00 - 4:45 p.m.</td>
<td><p><strong><u>Pulling the Threads Together</u></strong></p>
<p>One designated person presents a synthesis of the day’s deliberations with an overview of the key themes and ideas emerging, and any major recommendations and/or <strong>questions for policy makers</strong></p>
<p><strong>Synthesizer:</strong> Professor Michael Kempa</p>
<p><strong>Moderator:</strong> Dean Pam Sugiman</p>
</td>
</tr><tr><td>4:45 - 5:00 p.m.</td>
<td><p><strong>Closing</strong></p>
<p>Professor Steven Liss</p>
</td>
</tr></tbody></table>


